AB  - Roman law demonstrated a concern for public health and urban habitat, implementing regulations that, although primitive, shared objectives with our current environmental legislation. In Rome, the reuse of construction materials was considered legitimate due to its economic and architectural significance, prioritizing restoration over new construction and regulating reuse to prevent urban degradation. Likewise, there was a market for second-hand materials, tied to speculation from deliberate demolitions, and a functional approach to recycling for public works. Although waste was not prioritized as it is under the Circular Economy framework of Spain's Law 7/2022 on Waste and Contaminated Land, Roman practices foreshadowed embryonic forms of circular economy, emphasizing efficiency in debris management and material transportation. These precedents reflect principles that have influenced the shaping of modern environmental administrative law, aimed at mitigating urban ecological impacts and fostering resilience.
